    <p class="card__title"> HIEROGLYPHICS 1982 – 1992

</p>
    <p class="card__description">
Using simple imprints of everyday objects, stripped away everything unnecessary and reduced the image to pure form. It was the combination of signs that made them look like you could read them, as if they might be some forgotten ancient language. When hung together, they seemed to acquire a meaning of their own.
Diane Waldman, Deputy Director, Solomon Guggenheim Museum, New York City 1987
“The Guggenheim is happy to have acquired your work Hieroglyphics and is proud to have it as part of it's collection...”
Alexandra Tuttle
“...Reid's work hints at the underlying unity in the universe. Some of her symbols resemble sacred languages... Yet in a curious alchemy that only art can achieve, Reid manages to transform the banal signs of our civilization's mediocrity into a powerful secret universe.”
    </p>
